Durban - Police are still searching for Automatic Teller Machine (ATM) bombers who blew up a safe inside a bank in Ixopo in the KwaZulu-Natal midlands on Sunday. 
Private security company Berg Protection Services Drakensberg said that a gang of approximately 20 members heavily armed, blew the main safe at Capitech Bank.

Lieutenant Colonel Thulani Zwane a KwaZulu-Natal police spokesperson said the gang made off with an undisclosed amount of cash when they blew up the safe.
"The complainant alleged that on 4 August at about 11 am he received information that an ATM at his work place was bombed. He then proceeded to the scene. On arrival he went inside and found that two cash depositors were taken,"Zwane said.
A case robbery was opened at Ixopo police station for investigation.  

In March 2019, two alleged ATM bombers were shot dead in a shoot-out with police in the Durban CBD and two others were subsequently arrested. 
Police officers from the national intervention unit received intelligence of a group of heavily armed men in a minibus taxi and a sedan who were breaking into business premises on Anton Lembede (formerly Smith) Street with the aim of bombing ATM's and stealing from other businesses about 30 minutes after midnight said police spokesperson Colonel Thembeka Mbele.
